            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Yeah. I began to realize that much of what I suggest could also work as invisible/named/owned marks, but I think the desired uses probably more closely mirror the idea of cursors. All the features listed in that issue sound like things that would almost have to be re-implementations that already come with cursors. With additional cursor instances, you could get automatic secondary cursor visibility (or invisibility, if desired), and literally everything it’s already possible to do with cursors (including every command in every mode that depends on cursor position). Adding optional link-to-another-cursor and transform fields to the cursor class would further make multiple-cursor functionality trivially implementable in powerful ways.\r\n\r\nBut there are also things invisible/named/owned marks could do that could be very powerful when combined with multiple cursors. Mostly they involve preserving the *original* insertion point made before manipulating multiple cursors simultaneously. It would also allow you to make new marks while manipulating multiple cursors (one array of owned marks per create-a-mark-here command?) Even storing marks in arrays begins to make sense when you have multiple cursors. Going to an array of marks would automatically enter multiple-cursor mode. First entry in the array would probably have to be the location for the primary cursor.\r\n\r\nI also imagine that transformed cursors (and cursors whose content is taken to be transformed) would require ownership of a beginning mark and and end mark to keep track of what has been transformed. Might make things tricky if said range is manipulated directly, reducing the viability of the transformation idea. I say it’s usefulness outweighs the concerns, *if* a easy-to-understand schema for transform abandonment can be made clear to the user. It might also be useful to allow highlighting of nearby inactive cursors (and those cursors that one is tied to) and to allow jumping to the nearest untransformed cursor.\r\n\r\nAnd total lack of a link to an untransformed cursor might work if entry is done in the command line.",
